<font color="#FF0000">MEMORIES ARE ALL THEY HAVE.</font><br>
<tt>Wed Dec  3  2:22:43 US/Eastern 1997
</tt><p>
I have been in touch with several family members of servicemen who were killed in action or missing in action from my old unit, the 37th Aerospace Rescue and Recovery Squadron.  In my letters and e-mails to them, I learned that they are absorbed in learning all that they can about their lost loved ones.  It is also apparent, unfortunately, that the US Government has not been forthcoming in giving context to the events surrounding these losses, or in what these people were doing when they were lost.<br><br>
When I heard through our Pararescue Association that people were looking for information, stories, photos, etc., I looked through my scrap book and found photographs of their loved ones, as they were in DaNang.  I decided that I needed to copy them and get the pictures to them.  One, who has posted here, wrote back.  Let me share a little of what she wrote:<br><br>
“Thank you so very much for the photos of my dad!!!  One of them (the one with Al and the others welcoming back a Jolly Green) actually accompanied me as my ‘Focus Point’ when I gave birth to my son in January.  It helped me tremendously knowing that a little part of my dad was there that day.  You see, my son was six weeks early and even though I tried not to show it I was scared out of my mind.  Your picture helped me more than mere words can say.”<br><br>
Just now I taped a twenty-or-so minute movie that I had made while flying out of DaNang in 1971.  It’s not-so-good, but will at least give some of the loved ones of these pararescuemen some knowledge of what we saw while there.  It brought back a lot of my own memories too.<br><br>
What I’m proposing is that we change the focus of this forum a bit, and try to recall some of those who did not make it back, their lives, their fun times, their heroism, and give those memories to some of the survivors, their wives and children.  They are really hungry to find out more about how their husbands/fathers lived.  <br><br>
After all these years, there is still a yearning out there.  There is also a web site, Sons and Daughters In Touch, that I would encourage all Vietnam Vets to visit.  I’ll post the site soon.<br><br>

